{"cues": [{"duration": 5.038, "start": 0.0, "text": "If you feed a large language model the phrase, Michael Jordan plays the sport of blank,"}, {"duration": 4.522, "start": 5.038, "text": "and you have it predict what comes next, and it correctly predicts basketball,"}, {"duration": 4.695, "start": 9.56, "text": "this would suggest that somewhere, inside its hundreds of billions of parameters,"}, {"duration": 4.065, "start": 14.255, "text": "it's baked in knowledge about a specific person and his specific sport."}, {"duration": 3.206, "start": 18.94, "text": "And I think in general, anyone who's played around with one of these"}, {"duration": 3.254, "start": 22.146, "text": "models has the clear sense that it's memorized tons and tons of facts."}, {"duration": 3.46, "start": 25.7, "text": "So a reasonable question you could ask is, how exactly does that work?"}, {"duration": 1.88, "start": 29.16, "text": "And where do those facts live?"}, {"duration": 4.665, "start": 35.72, "text": "Last December, a few researchers from Google DeepMind posted about work on this question,"}, {"duration": 4.095, "start": 40.385, "text": "and they were using this specific example of matching athletes to their sports."}, {"duration": 4.924, "start": 44.9, "text": "And although a full mechanistic understanding of how facts are stored remains unsolved,"}, {"duration": 4.533, "start": 49.824, "text": "they had some interesting partial results, including the very general high-level"}, {"duration": 4.533, "start": 54.357, "text": "conclusion that the facts seem to live inside a specific part of these networks,"}, {"duration": 3.75, "start": 58.89, "text": "known fancifully as the multi-layer perceptrons, or MLPs for short."}, {"duration": 3.142, "start": 63.12, "text": "In the last couple of chapters, you and I have been digging into"}, {"duration": 4.062, "start": 66.262, "text": "the details behind transformers, the architecture underlying large language models,"}, {"duration": 2.176, "start": 70.324, "text": "and also underlying a lot of other modern AI."}, {"duration": 3.14, "start": 73.06, "text": "In the most recent chapter, we were focusing on a piece called Attention."}, {"duration": 4.124, "start": 76.84, "text": "And the next step for you and me is to dig into the details of what happens inside"}, {"duration": 4.076, "start": 80.964, "text": "these multi-layer perceptrons, which make up the other big portion of the network."}, {"duration": 2.394, "start": 85.68, "text": "The computation here is actually relatively simple,"}, {"duration": 2.026, "start": 88.074, "text": "especially when you compare it to attention."}, {"duration": 2.096, "start": 90.56, "text": "It boils down essentially to a pair of matrix"}, {"duration": 2.324, "start": 92.656, "text": "multiplications with a simple something in between."}, {"duration": 4.74, "start": 95.72, "text": "However, interpreting what these computations are doing is exceedingly challenging."}, {"duration": 4.106, "start": 101.56, "text": "Our main goal here is to step through the computations and make them memorable,"}, {"duration": 3.798, "start": 105.666, "text": "but I'd like to do it in the context of showing a specific example of how"}, {"duration": 3.696, "start": 109.464, "text": "one of these blocks could, at least in principle, store a concrete fact."}, {"duration": 3.5, "start": 113.58, "text": "Specifically, it'll be storing the fact that Michael Jordan plays basketball."}, {"duration": 2.688, "start": 118.08, "text": "I should mention the layout here is inspired by a conversation"}, {"duration": 2.432, "start": 120.768, "text": "I had with one of those DeepMind researchers, Neil Nanda."}, {"duration": 3.978, "start": 124.06, "text": "For the most part, I will assume that you've either watched the last two chapters,"}, {"duration": 3.019, "start": 128.038, "text": "or otherwise you have a basic sense for what a transformer is,"}, {"duration": 3.643, "start": 131.057, "text": "but refreshers never hurt, so here's the quick reminder of the overall flow."}, {"duration": 2.906, "start": 135.34, "text": "You and I have been studying a model that's trained"}, {"duration": 3.074, "start": 138.246, "text": "to take in a piece of text and predict what comes next."}, {"duration": 3.245, "start": 141.72, "text": "That input text is first broken into a bunch of tokens,"}, {"duration": 4.52, "start": 144.965, "text": "which means little chunks that are typically words or little pieces of words,"}, {"duration": 3.535, "start": 149.485, "text": "and each token is associated with a high-dimensional vector,"}, {"duration": 2.26, "start": 153.02, "text": "which is to say a long list of numbers."}, {"duration": 4.478, "start": 155.84, "text": "This sequence of vectors then repeatedly passes through two kinds of operation,"}, {"duration": 4.311, "start": 160.318, "text": "attention, which allows the vectors to pass information between one another,"}, {"duration": 4.479, "start": 164.629, "text": "and then the multilayer perceptrons, the thing that we're gonna dig into today,"}, {"duration": 3.192, "start": 169.108, "text": "and also there's a certain normalization step in between."}, {"duration": 3.131, "start": 173.3, "text": "After the sequence of vectors has flowed through many,"}, {"duration": 3.588, "start": 176.431, "text": "many different iterations of both of these blocks, by the end,"}, {"duration": 4.897, "start": 180.019, "text": "the hope is that each vector has soaked up enough information, both from the context,"}, {"duration": 4.441, "start": 184.916, "text": "all of the other words in the input, and also from the general knowledge that"}, {"duration": 2.904, "start": 189.357, "text": "was baked into the model weights through training,"}, {"duration": 3.759, "start": 192.261, "text": "that it can be used to make a prediction of what token comes next."}, {"duration": 3.822, "start": 196.86, "text": "One of the key ideas that I want you to have in your mind is that all of"}, {"duration": 3.09, "start": 200.682, "text": "these vectors live in a very, very high-dimensional space,"}, {"duration": 4.137, "start": 203.772, "text": "and when you think about that space, different directions can encode different"}, {"duration": 0.891, "start": 207.909, "text": "kinds of meaning."}, {"duration": 3.976, "start": 210.12, "text": "So a very classic example that I like to refer back to is how if you look"}, {"duration": 3.278, "start": 214.096, "text": "at the embedding of woman and subtract the embedding of man,"}, {"duration": 3.868, "start": 217.374, "text": "and you take that little step and you add it to another masculine noun,"}, {"duration": 2.526, "start": 221.242, "text": "something like uncle, you land somewhere very,"}, {"duration": 2.472, "start": 223.768, "text": "very close to the corresponding feminine noun."}, {"duration": 4.44, "start": 226.44, "text": "In this sense, this particular direction encodes gender information."}, {"duration": 3.974, "start": 231.64, "text": "The idea is that many other distinct directions in this super high-dimensional"}, {"duration": 4.026, "start": 235.614, "text": "space could correspond to other features that the model might want to represent."}, {"duration": 4.78, "start": 241.4, "text": "In a transformer, these vectors don't merely encode the meaning of a single word, though."}, {"duration": 4.308, "start": 246.68, "text": "As they flow through the network, they imbibe a much richer meaning based"}, {"duration": 4.192, "start": 250.988, "text": "on all the context around them, and also based on the model's knowledge."}, {"duration": 2.626, "start": 255.88, "text": "Ultimately, each one needs to encode something far,"}, {"duration": 3.839, "start": 258.506, "text": "far beyond the meaning of a single word, since it needs to be sufficient to"}, {"duration": 1.415, "start": 262.345, "text": "predict what will come next."}, {"duration": 3.92, "start": 264.56, "text": "We've already seen how attention blocks let you incorporate context,"}, {"duration": 4.318, "start": 268.48, "text": "but a majority of the model parameters actually live inside the MLP blocks,"}, {"duration": 4.489, "start": 272.798, "text": "and one thought for what they might be doing is that they offer extra capacity"}, {"duration": 0.853, "start": 277.287, "text": "to store facts."}, {"duration": 3.625, "start": 278.72, "text": "Like I said, the lesson here is gonna center on the concrete toy example"}, {"duration": 3.775, "start": 282.345, "text": "of how exactly it could store the fact that Michael Jordan plays basketball."}, {"duration": 2.41, "start": 287.12, "text": "Now, this toy example is gonna require that you and I make"}, {"duration": 2.37, "start": 289.53, "text": "a couple of assumptions about that high-dimensional space."}, {"duration": 4.631, "start": 292.36, "text": "First, we'll suppose that one of the directions represents the idea of a first name"}, {"duration": 4.632, "start": 296.991, "text": "Michael, and then another nearly perpendicular direction represents the idea of the"}, {"duration": 4.797, "start": 301.623, "text": "last name Jordan, and then yet a third direction will represent the idea of basketball."}, {"duration": 3.721, "start": 307.4, "text": "So specifically, what I mean by this is if you look in the network and"}, {"duration": 2.621, "start": 311.121, "text": "you pluck out one of the vectors being processed,"}, {"duration": 3.46, "start": 313.742, "text": "if its dot product with this first name Michael direction is one,"}, {"duration": 3.67, "start": 317.202, "text": "that's what it would mean for the vector to be encoding the idea of a"}, {"duration": 1.468, "start": 320.872, "text": "person with that first name."}, {"duration": 2.343, "start": 323.8, "text": "Otherwise, that dot product would be zero or negative,"}, {"duration": 2.557, "start": 326.143, "text": "meaning the vector doesn't really align with that direction."}, {"duration": 2.797, "start": 329.42, "text": "And for simplicity, let's completely ignore the very reasonable"}, {"duration": 3.103, "start": 332.217, "text": "question of what it might mean if that dot product was bigger than one."}, {"duration": 3.631, "start": 336.2, "text": "Similarly, its dot product with these other directions would"}, {"duration": 3.929, "start": 339.831, "text": "tell you whether it represents the last name Jordan or basketball."}, {"duration": 4.051, "start": 344.74, "text": "So let's say a vector is meant to represent the full name, Michael Jordan,"}, {"duration": 3.889, "start": 348.791, "text": "then its dot product with both of these directions would have to be one."}, {"duration": 3.178, "start": 353.48, "text": "Since the text Michael Jordan spans two different tokens,"}, {"duration": 4.822, "start": 356.658, "text": "this would also mean we have to assume that an earlier attention block has successfully"}, {"duration": 4.493, "start": 361.48, "text": "passed information to the second of these two vectors so as to ensure that it can"}, {"duration": 0.987, "start": 365.973, "text": "encode both names."}, {"duration": 3.54, "start": 367.94, "text": "With all of those as the assumptions, let's now dive into the meat of the lesson."}, {"duration": 3.1, "start": 371.88, "text": "What happens inside a multilayer perceptron?"}, {"duration": 4.266, "start": 377.1, "text": "You might think of this sequence of vectors flowing into the block, and remember,"}, {"duration": 4.214, "start": 381.366, "text": "each vector was originally associated with one of the tokens from the input text."}, {"duration": 3.362, "start": 386.08, "text": "What's gonna happen is that each individual vector from that sequence"}, {"duration": 3.795, "start": 389.442, "text": "goes through a short series of operations, we'll unpack them in just a moment,"}, {"duration": 3.123, "start": 393.237, "text": "and at the end, we'll get another vector with the same dimension."}, {"duration": 4.119, "start": 396.88, "text": "That other vector is gonna get added to the original one that flowed in,"}, {"duration": 2.201, "start": 400.999, "text": "and that sum is the result flowing out."}, {"duration": 4.226, "start": 403.72, "text": "This sequence of operations is something you apply to every vector in the sequence,"}, {"duration": 3.674, "start": 407.946, "text": "associated with every token in the input, and it all happens in parallel."}, {"duration": 2.505, "start": 412.1, "text": "In particular, the vectors don't talk to each other in this step,"}, {"duration": 1.595, "start": 414.605, "text": "they're all kind of doing their own thing."}, {"duration": 2.629, "start": 416.72, "text": "And for you and me, that actually makes it a lot simpler,"}, {"duration": 2.993, "start": 419.349, "text": "because it means if we understand what happens to just one of the"}, {"duration": 3.718, "start": 422.342, "text": "vectors through this block, we effectively understand what happens to all of them."}, {"duration": 4.28, "start": 427.1, "text": "When I say this block is gonna encode the fact that Michael Jordan plays basketball,"}, {"duration": 4.129, "start": 431.38, "text": "what I mean is that if a vector flows in that encodes first name Michael and last"}, {"duration": 4.28, "start": 435.509, "text": "name Jordan, then this sequence of computations will produce something that includes"}, {"duration": 4.231, "start": 439.789, "text": "that direction basketball, which is what will add on to the vector in that position."}, {"duration": 4.1, "start": 445.6, "text": "The first step of this process looks like multiplying that vector by a very big matrix."}, {"duration": 1.94, "start": 450.04, "text": "No surprises there, this is deep learning."}, {"duration": 2.555, "start": 452.68, "text": "And this matrix, like all of the other ones we've seen,"}, {"duration": 2.738, "start": 455.235, "text": "is filled with model parameters that are learned from data,"}, {"duration": 3.468, "start": 457.973, "text": "which you might think of as a bunch of knobs and dials that get tweaked and"}, {"duration": 2.099, "start": 461.441, "text": "tuned to determine what the model behavior is."}, {"duration": 4.178, "start": 464.5, "text": "Now, one nice way to think about matrix multiplication is to imagine each row of"}, {"duration": 4.126, "start": 468.678, "text": "that matrix as being its own vector, and taking a bunch of dot products between"}, {"duration": 4.076, "start": 472.804, "text": "those rows and the vector being processed, which I'll label as E for embedding."}, {"duration": 3.296, "start": 477.28, "text": "For example, suppose that very first row happened to equal"}, {"duration": 3.464, "start": 480.576, "text": "this first name Michael direction that we're presuming exists."}, {"duration": 5.091, "start": 484.32, "text": "That would mean that the first component in this output, this dot product right here,"}, {"duration": 3.553, "start": 489.411, "text": "would be one if that vector encodes the first name Michael,"}, {"duration": 1.836, "start": 492.964, "text": "and zero or negative otherwise."}, {"duration": 3.625, "start": 495.88, "text": "Even more fun, take a moment to think about what it would mean if that"}, {"duration": 3.575, "start": 499.505, "text": "first row was this first name Michael plus last name Jordan direction."}, {"duration": 3.72, "start": 503.7, "text": "And for simplicity, let me go ahead and write that down as M plus J."}, {"duration": 2.851, "start": 508.08, "text": "Then, taking a dot product with this embedding E,"}, {"duration": 4.049, "start": 510.931, "text": "things distribute really nicely, so it looks like M dot E plus J dot E."}, {"duration": 4.802, "start": 514.98, "text": "And notice how that means the ultimate value would be two if the vector encodes the"}, {"duration": 4.918, "start": 519.782, "text": "full name Michael Jordan, and otherwise it would be one or something smaller than one."}, {"duration": 1.92, "start": 525.34, "text": "And that's just one row in this matrix."}, {"duration": 4.271, "start": 527.6, "text": "You might think of all of the other rows as in parallel asking some other kinds of"}, {"duration": 4.169, "start": 531.871, "text": "questions, probing at some other sorts of features of the vector being processed."}, {"duration": 3.216, "start": 536.7, "text": "Very often this step also involves adding another vector to the output,"}, {"duration": 2.324, "start": 539.916, "text": "which is full of model parameters learned from data."}, {"duration": 2.32, "start": 542.24, "text": "This other vector is known as the bias."}, {"duration": 3.387, "start": 545.18, "text": "For our example, I want you to imagine that the value of this"}, {"duration": 2.786, "start": 548.567, "text": "bias in that very first component is negative one,"}, {"duration": 4.207, "start": 551.353, "text": "meaning our final output looks like that relevant dot product, but minus one."}, {"duration": 3.871, "start": 556.12, "text": "You might very reasonably ask why I would want you to assume that the"}, {"duration": 3.927, "start": 559.991, "text": "model has learned this, and in a moment you'll see why it's very clean"}, {"duration": 4.149, "start": 563.918, "text": "and nice if we have a value here which is positive if and only if a vector"}, {"duration": 4.093, "start": 568.067, "text": "encodes the full name Michael Jordan, and otherwise it's zero or negative."}, {"duration": 3.228, "start": 573.04, "text": "The total number of rows in this matrix, which is something"}, {"duration": 3.444, "start": 576.268, "text": "like the number of questions being asked, in the case of GPT-3,"}, {"duration": 3.068, "start": 579.712, "text": "whose numbers we've been following, is just under 50,000."}, {"duration": 3.54, "start": 583.1, "text": "In fact, it's exactly four times the number of dimensions in this embedding space."}, {"duration": 0.98, "start": 586.92, "text": "That's a design choice."}, {"duration": 1.876, "start": 587.94, "text": "You could make it more, you could make it less,"}, {"duration": 2.424, "start": 589.816, "text": "but having a clean multiple tends to be friendly for hardware."}, {"duration": 4.205, "start": 592.74, "text": "Since this matrix full of weights maps us into a higher dimensional space,"}, {"duration": 2.075, "start": 596.945, "text": "I'm gonna give it the shorthand W up."}, {"duration": 3.314, "start": 599.02, "text": "I'll continue labeling the vector we're processing as E,"}, {"duration": 4.826, "start": 602.334, "text": "and let's label this bias vector as B up and put that all back down in the diagram."}, {"duration": 3.776, "start": 609.18, "text": "At this point, a problem is that this operation is purely linear,"}, {"duration": 2.404, "start": 612.956, "text": "but language is a very non-linear process."}, {"duration": 3.898, "start": 615.88, "text": "If the entry that we're measuring is high for Michael plus Jordan,"}, {"duration": 4.132, "start": 619.778, "text": "it would also necessarily be somewhat triggered by Michael plus Phelps"}, {"duration": 4.19, "start": 623.91, "text": "and also Alexis plus Jordan, despite those being unrelated conceptually."}, {"duration": 3.46, "start": 628.54, "text": "What you really want is a simple yes or no for the full name."}, {"duration": 2.543, "start": 632.9, "text": "So the next step is to pass this large intermediate"}, {"duration": 2.397, "start": 635.443, "text": "vector through a very simple non-linear function."}, {"duration": 3.443, "start": 638.36, "text": "A common choice is one that takes all of the negative values and"}, {"duration": 3.497, "start": 641.803, "text": "maps them to zero and leaves all of the positive values unchanged."}, {"duration": 4.304, "start": 646.44, "text": "And continuing with the deep learning tradition of overly fancy names,"}, {"duration": 5.276, "start": 650.744, "text": "this very simple function is often called the rectified linear unit, or ReLU for short."}, {"duration": 1.86, "start": 656.02, "text": "Here's what the graph looks like."}, {"duration": 5.072, "start": 658.3, "text": "So taking our imagined example where this first entry of the intermediate vector is one,"}, {"duration": 4.502, "start": 663.372, "text": "if and only if the full name is Michael Jordan and zero or negative otherwise,"}, {"duration": 4.389, "start": 667.874, "text": "after you pass it through the ReLU, you end up with a very clean value where"}, {"duration": 3.477, "start": 672.263, "text": "all of the zero and negative values just get clipped to zero."}, {"duration": 3.68, "start": 676.1, "text": "So this output would be one for the full name Michael Jordan and zero otherwise."}, {"duration": 3.56, "start": 680.56, "text": "In other words, it very directly mimics the behavior of an AND gate."}, {"duration": 3.592, "start": 685.66, "text": "Often models will use a slightly modified function that's called the GELU,"}, {"duration": 2.768, "start": 689.252, "text": "which has the same basic shape, it's just a bit smoother."}, {"duration": 3.22, "start": 692.5, "text": "But for our purposes, it's a little bit cleaner if we only think about the ReLU."}, {"duration": 3.406, "start": 696.74, "text": "Also, when you hear people refer to the neurons of a transformer,"}, {"duration": 2.374, "start": 700.146, "text": "they're talking about these values right here."}, {"duration": 4.49, "start": 702.9, "text": "Whenever you see that common neural network picture with a layer of dots and a"}, {"duration": 4.888, "start": 707.39, "text": "bunch of lines connecting to the previous layer, which we had earlier in this series,"}, {"duration": 3.866, "start": 712.278, "text": "that's typically meant to convey this combination of a linear step,"}, {"duration": 5.116, "start": 716.144, "text": "a matrix multiplication, followed by some simple term-wise nonlinear function like a ReLU."}, {"duration": 3.318, "start": 722.5, "text": "You would say that this neuron is active whenever this value"}, {"duration": 3.102, "start": 725.818, "text": "is positive and that it's inactive if that value is zero."}, {"duration": 2.26, "start": 730.12, "text": "The next step looks very similar to the first one."}, {"duration": 4.02, "start": 732.56, "text": "You multiply by a very large matrix and you add on a certain bias term."}, {"duration": 4.167, "start": 736.98, "text": "In this case, the number of dimensions in the output is back down to the size of"}, {"duration": 4.373, "start": 741.147, "text": "that embedding space, so I'm gonna go ahead and call this the down projection matrix."}, {"duration": 2.687, "start": 746.22, "text": "And this time, instead of thinking of things row by row,"}, {"duration": 2.453, "start": 748.907, "text": "it's actually nicer to think of it column by column."}, {"duration": 4.392, "start": 751.86, "text": "You see, another way that you can hold matrix multiplication in your head is to"}, {"duration": 4.446, "start": 756.252, "text": "imagine taking each column of the matrix and multiplying it by the corresponding"}, {"duration": 4.942, "start": 760.698, "text": "term in the vector that it's processing and adding together all of those rescaled columns."}, {"duration": 4.521, "start": 766.84, "text": "The reason it's nicer to think about this way is because here the columns have the same"}, {"duration": 4.419, "start": 771.361, "text": "dimension as the embedding space, so we can think of them as directions in that space."}, {"duration": 3.545, "start": 776.14, "text": "For instance, we will imagine that the model has learned to make that"}, {"duration": 3.395, "start": 779.685, "text": "first column into this basketball direction that we suppose exists."}, {"duration": 4.27, "start": 784.18, "text": "What that would mean is that when the relevant neuron in that first position is active,"}, {"duration": 2.33, "start": 788.45, "text": "we'll be adding this column to the final result."}, {"duration": 4.64, "start": 791.14, "text": "But if that neuron was inactive, if that number was zero, then this would have no effect."}, {"duration": 1.56, "start": 796.5, "text": "And it doesn't just have to be basketball."}, {"duration": 3.418, "start": 798.22, "text": "The model could also bake into this column and many other features that"}, {"duration": 3.562, "start": 801.638, "text": "it wants to associate with something that has the full name Michael Jordan."}, {"duration": 4.871, "start": 806.98, "text": "And at the same time, all of the other columns in this matrix are telling you"}, {"duration": 4.809, "start": 811.851, "text": "what will be added to the final result if the corresponding neuron is active."}, {"duration": 3.094, "start": 817.36, "text": "And if you have a bias in this case, it's something that you're"}, {"duration": 3.046, "start": 820.454, "text": "just adding every single time, regardless of the neuron values."}, {"duration": 1.22, "start": 824.06, "text": "You might wonder what's that doing."}, {"duration": 3.78, "start": 825.54, "text": "As with all parameter-filled objects here, it's kind of hard to say exactly."}, {"duration": 2.967, "start": 829.32, "text": "Maybe there's some bookkeeping that the network needs to do,"}, {"duration": 2.093, "start": 832.287, "text": "but you can feel free to ignore it for now."}, {"duration": 2.878, "start": 834.86, "text": "Making our notation a little more compact again,"}, {"duration": 4.7, "start": 837.738, "text": "I'll call this big matrix W down and similarly call that bias vector B down and"}, {"duration": 1.822, "start": 842.438, "text": "put that back into our diagram."}, {"duration": 4.378, "start": 844.74, "text": "Like I previewed earlier, what you do with this final result is add it to the vector"}, {"duration": 4.122, "start": 849.118, "text": "that flowed into the block at that position and that gets you this final result."}, {"duration": 5.24, "start": 853.82, "text": "So for example, if the vector flowing in encoded both first name Michael and last name"}, {"duration": 4.638, "start": 859.06, "text": "Jordan, then because this sequence of operations will trigger that AND gate,"}, {"duration": 4.999, "start": 863.698, "text": "it will add on the basketball direction, so what pops out will encode all of those"}, {"duration": 0.543, "start": 868.697, "text": "together."}, {"duration": 4.38, "start": 869.82, "text": "And remember, this is a process happening to every one of those vectors in parallel."}, {"duration": 4.967, "start": 874.8, "text": "In particular, taking the GPT-3 numbers, it means that this block doesn't just"}, {"duration": 5.093, "start": 879.767, "text": "have 50,000 neurons in it, it has 50,000 times the number of tokens in the input."}, {"duration": 3.176, "start": 888.18, "text": "So that is the entire operation, two matrix products,"}, {"duration": 3.824, "start": 891.356, "text": "each with a bias added and a simple clipping function in between."}, {"duration": 3.335, "start": 896.08, "text": "Any of you who watched the earlier videos of the series will recognize this"}, {"duration": 3.205, "start": 899.415, "text": "structure as the most basic kind of neural network that we studied there."}, {"duration": 3.02, "start": 903.08, "text": "In that example, it was trained to recognize handwritten digits."}, {"duration": 4.224, "start": 906.58, "text": "Over here, in the context of a transformer for a large language model,"}, {"duration": 4.284, "start": 910.804, "text": "this is one piece in a larger architecture and any attempt to interpret"}, {"duration": 4.343, "start": 915.088, "text": "what exactly it's doing is heavily intertwined with the idea of encoding"}, {"duration": 3.749, "start": 919.431, "text": "information into vectors of a high-dimensional embedding space."}, {"duration": 4.34, "start": 924.26, "text": "That is the core lesson, but I do wanna step back and reflect on two different things,"}, {"duration": 3.443, "start": 928.6, "text": "the first of which is a kind of bookkeeping, and the second of which"}, {"duration": 3.392, "start": 932.043, "text": "involves a very thought-provoking fact about higher dimensions that"}, {"duration": 2.645, "start": 935.435, "text": "I actually didn't know until I dug into transformers."}, {"duration": 4.867, "start": 941.08, "text": "In the last two chapters, you and I started counting up the total number of parameters"}, {"duration": 4.813, "start": 945.947, "text": "in GPT-3 and seeing exactly where they live, so let's quickly finish up the game here."}, {"duration": 5.39, "start": 951.4, "text": "I already mentioned how this up projection matrix has just under 50,000 rows and"}, {"duration": 5.39, "start": 956.79, "text": "that each row matches the size of the embedding space, which for GPT-3 is 12,288."}, {"duration": 5.277, "start": 963.24, "text": "Multiplying those together, it gives us 604 million parameters just for that matrix,"}, {"duration": 5.403, "start": 968.517, "text": "and the down projection has the same number of parameters just with a transposed shape."}, {"duration": 2.9, "start": 974.5, "text": "So together, they give about 1.2 billion parameters."}, {"duration": 2.605, "start": 978.28, "text": "The bias vector also accounts for a couple more parameters,"}, {"duration": 3.215, "start": 980.885, "text": "but it's a trivial proportion of the total, so I'm not even gonna show it."}, {"duration": 4.952, "start": 984.66, "text": "In GPT-3, this sequence of embedding vectors flows through not one,"}, {"duration": 4.661, "start": 989.612, "text": "but 96 distinct MLPs, so the total number of parameters devoted"}, {"duration": 3.787, "start": 994.273, "text": "to all of these blocks adds up to about 116 billion."}, {"duration": 3.357, "start": 998.82, "text": "This is around 2 thirds of the total parameters in the network,"}, {"duration": 4.197, "start": 1002.177, "text": "and when you add it to everything that we had before, for the attention blocks,"}, {"duration": 4.091, "start": 1006.374, "text": "the embedding, and the unembedding, you do indeed get that grand total of 175"}, {"duration": 1.155, "start": 1010.465, "text": "billion as advertised."}, {"duration": 3.577, "start": 1013.06, "text": "It's probably worth mentioning there's another set of parameters associated"}, {"duration": 3.342, "start": 1016.637, "text": "with those normalization steps that this explanation has skipped over,"}, {"duration": 3.861, "start": 1019.979, "text": "but like the bias vector, they account for a very trivial proportion of the total."}, {"duration": 3.26, "start": 1025.9, "text": "As to that second point of reflection, you might be wondering if"}, {"duration": 3.059, "start": 1029.16, "text": "this central toy example we've been spending so much time on"}, {"duration": 3.461, "start": 1032.219, "text": "reflects how facts are actually stored in real large language models."}, {"duration": 3.449, "start": 1036.319, "text": "It is true that the rows of that first matrix can be thought of as"}, {"duration": 3.808, "start": 1039.768, "text": "directions in this embedding space, and that means the activation of each"}, {"duration": 3.964, "start": 1043.576, "text": "neuron tells you how much a given vector aligns with some specific direction."}, {"duration": 3.208, "start": 1047.76, "text": "It's also true that the columns of that second matrix tell"}, {"duration": 3.372, "start": 1050.968, "text": "you what will be added to the result if that neuron is active."}, {"duration": 2.16, "start": 1054.64, "text": "Both of those are just mathematical facts."}, {"duration": 4.066, "start": 1057.74, "text": "However, the evidence does suggest that individual neurons very rarely"}, {"duration": 3.093, "start": 1061.806, "text": "represent a single clean feature like Michael Jordan,"}, {"duration": 3.608, "start": 1064.899, "text": "and there may actually be a very good reason this is the case,"}, {"duration": 4.009, "start": 1068.507, "text": "related to an idea floating around interpretability researchers these"}, {"duration": 1.604, "start": 1072.516, "text": "days known as superposition."}, {"duration": 3.917, "start": 1074.64, "text": "This is a hypothesis that might help to explain both why the models are"}, {"duration": 3.863, "start": 1078.557, "text": "especially hard to interpret and also why they scale surprisingly well."}, {"duration": 3.886, "start": 1083.5, "text": "The basic idea is that if you have an n-dimensional space and you wanna"}, {"duration": 3.779, "start": 1087.386, "text": "represent a bunch of different features using directions that are all"}, {"duration": 2.915, "start": 1091.165, "text": "perpendicular to one another in that space, you know,"}, {"duration": 2.7, "start": 1094.08, "text": "that way if you add a component in one direction,"}, {"duration": 2.699, "start": 1096.78, "text": "it doesn't influence any of the other directions,"}, {"duration": 4.481, "start": 1099.479, "text": "then the maximum number of vectors you can fit is only n, the number of dimensions."}, {"duration": 3.02, "start": 1104.6, "text": "To a mathematician, actually, this is the definition of dimension."}, {"duration": 2.653, "start": 1108.22, "text": "But where it gets interesting is if you relax that"}, {"duration": 2.707, "start": 1110.873, "text": "constraint a little bit and you tolerate some noise."}, {"duration": 4.529, "start": 1114.18, "text": "Say you allow those features to be represented by vectors that aren't exactly"}, {"duration": 5.111, "start": 1118.709, "text": "perpendicular, they're just nearly perpendicular, maybe between 89 and 91 degrees apart."}, {"duration": 3.2, "start": 1124.82, "text": "If we were in two or three dimensions, this makes no difference."}, {"duration": 3.348, "start": 1128.26, "text": "That gives you hardly any extra wiggle room to fit more vectors in,"}, {"duration": 3.596, "start": 1131.608, "text": "which makes it all the more counterintuitive that for higher dimensions,"}, {"duration": 1.576, "start": 1135.204, "text": "the answer changes dramatically."}, {"duration": 4.185, "start": 1137.66, "text": "I can give you a really quick and dirty illustration of this using some"}, {"duration": 4.243, "start": 1141.845, "text": "scrappy Python that's going to create a list of 100-dimensional vectors,"}, {"duration": 5.231, "start": 1146.088, "text": "each one initialized randomly, and this list is going to contain 10,000 distinct vectors,"}, {"duration": 3.081, "start": 1151.319, "text": "so 100 times as many vectors as there are dimensions."}, {"duration": 4.58, "start": 1155.32, "text": "This plot right here shows the distribution of angles between pairs of these vectors."}, {"duration": 4.713, "start": 1160.68, "text": "So because they started at random, those angles could be anything from 0 to 180 degrees,"}, {"duration": 3.283, "start": 1165.393, "text": "but you'll notice that already, even just for random vectors,"}, {"duration": 3.284, "start": 1168.676, "text": "there's this heavy bias for things to be closer to 90 degrees."}, {"duration": 4.669, "start": 1172.5, "text": "Then what I'm going to do is run a certain optimization process that iteratively nudges"}, {"duration": 4.351, "start": 1177.169, "text": "all of these vectors so that they try to become more perpendicular to one another."}, {"duration": 2.473, "start": 1182.06, "text": "After repeating this many different times, here's"}, {"duration": 2.127, "start": 1184.533, "text": "what the distribution of angles looks like."}, {"duration": 4.699, "start": 1187.12, "text": "We have to actually zoom in on it here because all of the possible angles"}, {"duration": 5.081, "start": 1191.819, "text": "between pairs of vectors sit inside this narrow range between 89 and 91 degrees."}, {"duration": 4.197, "start": 1198.02, "text": "In general, a consequence of something known as the Johnson-Lindenstrauss"}, {"duration": 4.425, "start": 1202.217, "text": "lemma is that the number of vectors you can cram into a space that are nearly"}, {"duration": 4.198, "start": 1206.642, "text": "perpendicular like this grows exponentially with the number of dimensions."}, {"duration": 2.86, "start": 1211.96, "text": "This is very significant for large language models,"}, {"duration": 3.685, "start": 1214.82, "text": "which might benefit from associating independent ideas with nearly"}, {"duration": 1.375, "start": 1218.505, "text": "perpendicular directions."}, {"duration": 2.596, "start": 1220.0, "text": "It means that it's possible for it to store many,"}, {"duration": 3.844, "start": 1222.596, "text": "many more ideas than there are dimensions in the space that it's allotted."}, {"duration": 4.42, "start": 1227.32, "text": "This might partially explain why model performance seems to scale so well with size."}, {"duration": 3.776, "start": 1232.54, "text": "A space that has 10 times as many dimensions can store way,"}, {"duration": 3.084, "start": 1236.316, "text": "way more than 10 times as many independent ideas."}, {"duration": 3.451, "start": 1240.42, "text": "And this is relevant not just to that embedding space where the vectors"}, {"duration": 3.452, "start": 1243.871, "text": "flowing through the model live, but also to that vector full of neurons"}, {"duration": 3.117, "start": 1247.323, "text": "in the middle of that multilayer perceptron that we just studied."}, {"duration": 5.153, "start": 1250.96, "text": "That is to say, at the sizes of GPT-3, it might not just be probing at 50,000 features,"}, {"duration": 3.865, "start": 1256.113, "text": "but if it instead leveraged this enormous added capacity by using"}, {"duration": 4.392, "start": 1259.978, "text": "nearly perpendicular directions of the space, it could be probing at many,"}, {"duration": 2.87, "start": 1264.37, "text": "many more features of the vector being processed."}, {"duration": 3.146, "start": 1267.78, "text": "But if it was doing that, what it means is that individual"}, {"duration": 3.414, "start": 1270.926, "text": "features aren't gonna be visible as a single neuron lighting up."}, {"duration": 4.72, "start": 1274.66, "text": "It would have to look like some specific combination of neurons instead, a superposition."}, {"duration": 3.915, "start": 1280.4, "text": "For any of you curious to learn more, a key relevant search term here is sparse"}, {"duration": 4.111, "start": 1284.315, "text": "autoencoder, which is a tool that some of the interpretability people use to try to"}, {"duration": 4.062, "start": 1288.426, "text": "extract what the true features are, even if they're very superimposed on all these"}, {"duration": 0.392, "start": 1292.488, "text": "neurons."}, {"duration": 3.26, "start": 1293.54, "text": "I'll link to a couple really great anthropic posts all about this."}, {"duration": 3.09, "start": 1297.88, "text": "At this point, we haven't touched every detail of a transformer,"}, {"duration": 2.33, "start": 1300.97, "text": "but you and I have hit the most important points."}, {"duration": 4.12, "start": 1303.52, "text": "The main thing that I wanna cover in a next chapter is the training process."}, {"duration": 3.469, "start": 1308.46, "text": "On the one hand, the short answer for how training works is that it's all"}, {"duration": 3.892, "start": 1311.929, "text": "backpropagation, and we covered backpropagation in a separate context with earlier"}, {"duration": 1.079, "start": 1315.821, "text": "chapters in the series."}, {"duration": 4.814, "start": 1317.22, "text": "But there is more to discuss, like the specific cost function used for language models,"}, {"duration": 4.049, "start": 1322.034, "text": "the idea of fine-tuning using reinforcement learning with human feedback,"}, {"duration": 1.697, "start": 1326.083, "text": "and the notion of scaling laws."}, {"duration": 2.153, "start": 1328.96, "text": "Quick note for the active followers among you,"}, {"duration": 3.573, "start": 1331.113, "text": "there are a number of non-machine learning-related videos that I'm excited to"}, {"duration": 3.481, "start": 1334.686, "text": "sink my teeth into before I make that next chapter, so it might be a while,"}, {"duration": 1.833, "start": 1338.167, "text": "but I do promise it'll come in due time."}, {"duration": 2.28, "start": 1355.64, "text": "Thank you."}], "video_id": "9-Jl0dxWQs8"}